Answer.Ans1: When AC/DC started in 1973, their label was Albert Productions. Albert Productions is an Australian record label founded by Ted Albert and headquartered in Sydney, Australia. AC/DC's connection with Albert Productions was established through their partnership with producers Harry Vanda and George Young, who were also members of the band Marcus Hook Roll Band. Under Albert Productions, AC/DC released their early albums, including their debut album "High Voltage" in 1975, helping to launch their career and establish their signature sound.
Answer.Res1: The reason AC/DC was signed to Albert Productions when they started in 1973 is because the label was owned and operated by the Young family. The Young brothers, Angus and Malcolm, were the founding members of AC/DC, and their older brother George Young and his songwriting partner Harry Vanda were key figures in the Australian music industry. The connection and family ties between the Young brothers and Albert Productions led to AC/DC being signed to the label, providing them with the opportunity to release their music and gain recognition in the music industry. Albert Productions played a crucial role in launching AC/DC's career and helping them establish themselves as one of the most successful rock bands in history.
